<h2 id="view-vs-cte">View vs CTE</h2>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Ad-hoc queries</strong>: For queries that are referenced occasionally (or just once), itâ€™s usually better to use a CTE. If you need the query again, you can just copy the CTE and modify it if necessary.</li>
  <li><strong>Frequently used queries</strong>: If you tend to reference the same query often, creating a corresponding view is a good idea. However, youâ€™ll need create view permission in your database to create a view.</li>
  <li><strong>Access management</strong>: A view might be used to restrict particular usersâ€™ database access while still allowing them to get the information they need. You can give users access to specific views that query the data theyâ€™re allowed to see without exposing the whole database. In such a case, a view provides an additional access layer.</li>
</ul>

